text: I hate sequels! Especially to movies that weren't all that good in the first place, i.e Fast and the Furious, Pirates of the Caribbean, and ANYTHING Marvel-related. I also hate movies that are simply reboots of movies that already exist, i.e Total Recall and the upcoming Robocop and Godzilla. BUT...this adaptation of The Planet of the Apes just blows my mind! The story is clever and explores the topic of human exceptionalism. When I heard that a sequel to RPA was in production I feared that it would simply be a stain on the reboot. But after watching this trailer I can say I have just a bit more hope that I will not be disappointed. Whereas a series like Iron Man releases movie after movie of the same plot with a new suit or in the case of Iron Man 3 a team of "Ironmen", DPA looks to expand upon its reboot in a way that will be much more fulfilling. Taking the idea of human exeptionalism introduced in the first film the sequel will turn the tables so to speak and reverse this idea. The ego of man will remain and humanity will fight to win back its title at the top of the food chain. I can't wait to see how events unfold. Thank you to the producers for investing in originality rather than a souped up "new suit."

text: So...obviously this movie raises a lot of questions. ¬†Here are a few just off the top of my head.  1. Where did the apes get the horses? ¬†They weren't just lying around in the woods so obviously they had to find them somewhere. ¬†Also, how did they learn how to ride them? ¬†None of them know how and it's clear humans didn't teach them.  2. Why are so many humans dead from the virus? ¬†The only way we see it get transmitted in the first movie is when one guy gets sprayed in the face and the other guy gets sneezed on in the face. ¬†Seems like it gets spread similar to the flu. Do you guys remember that one time when one airplane pilot got the flu and then everybody in the world got the flu?  3. How did apes from the zoo get so smart? ¬†Caesar only infected the 50 or so at the Ape Facility. ¬†The ones at the zoo just kind of become smart without explanation. ¬†Also, how are any of the other apes in the world getting smart? ¬†Is some infected person going around sneezing in their faces? ¬†  4. Why are there so many apes here? ¬†There were only 50 or so from the facility and then some more at the zoo. ¬†Where did the other ones come from? ¬†And how did they get infected? ¬†Furthermore, how did they contact each other? ¬†Even if the other ones got smart somehow they wouldn't be able to communicate over long distance because Caesar is the only one who can write and the only one who can understand any human language.  5. Back to the number of apes. ¬†There are maybe 700,000 on the planet right now. ¬†If every single one gets infected somehow, and by some miracle they all band together despite not being able to communicate with one another, the virus would have to wipe out something like 99.9% of all humans before the apes were only out numbered 10 to 1. ¬†Given the fact that the apes have no knowledge of warfare or war tactics and no knowledge of science and technology I'd say the odds are pretty much zero that they would have any chance of winning a war with humans.  6. ¬†How did they manage to make a Planet of the Apes film that has more plot holes then the Marky Mark version?

text: LETS READ THE MOVIE....... Starting in 2018, the wake of the ALZ-113 virus causes the collapse of human civilization. Ten years later, Caesar leads and governs a new generation of apes in a community located in the Muir Woods. While walking through the forest, Caesar's son Blue Eyes and Ash, the son of another chimpanzee, encounter a human. The human, Carver, panics and shoots Ash, wounding him. Carver calls for the rest of his small party of armed survivors, led by a man named Malcolm, while Blue Eyes calls for the other apes. Caesar orders the humans to leave. The remaining humans in San Francisco, genetically immune to the virus, are living in a guarded tower within the ruined city. Prompted by Koba, a scarred bonobo who holds a grudge against humans for his mistreatment, Caesar brings the apes to the city where he orders the humans to never enter ape territory again.  Malcolm convinces his fellow leader Dreyfus to give him three days to reconcile with the apes to gain access to a hydroelectric dam in their territory, which could provide long-term power to the city. Dreyfus, distrustful of the apes, arms survivors using an abandoned armory. Caesar allows Malcolm to work on the dam's generator, provided they surrender their guns. As Malcolm, his partner Ellie, and son Alexander work, they bond with the apes. Meanwhile, Koba discovers the armory and confronts Caesar, questioning his allegiance. In response, Caesar heavily beats Koba, but refuses to kill him and forgives him. Koba returns to the armory and, after murdering two human guards, steals an assault rifle. He then kills Carver, stealing his lighter.  The dam is eventually repaired, restoring power to the city. During the celebration, Koba, unnoticed, lights the apes' home on fire. Caesar notices Koba right before Koba shoots him in the arm, unseen by anyone else. In the panic of the shooting and the fire, Koba claims that Malcolm's group is responsible and orders the apes to war against the humans. Malcolm's group hides as Koba leads the apes to San Francisco. They plunder the armory and charge the tower‚Äôs gates. Despite heavy casualties, the apes overrun the tower and imprison all the humans as Dreyfus flees underground. When Ash refuses Koba‚Äôs orders to kill unarmed humans, citing Caesar's teachings, Koba kills Ash and jails all apes loyal to Caesar.  Malcolm's group find Caesar barely alive and transport him to his former home in San Francisco. Caesar reveals to Malcolm that Koba shot him, realizing his notion that all apes were better than humans was naive. As he enters the city to find medical supplies so Ellie can operate on Caesar, Malcom encounters Blue Eyes and reunites the two. Blue Eyes then frees the caged humans, as well as the apes loyal to Caesar. The freed apes join Caesar and confront Koba at the summit of the tower. Traveling with the apes, Malcolm locates Dreyfus, who informs Malcolm that his men have made radio contact with more survivors on their way to help fight the apes. While Caesar and Koba battle, Malcolm tries to prevent Dreyfus from detonating C-4 explosives underneath the tower. Dreyfus eventually detonates them; the resulting explosion kills Dreyfus and collapses part of the tower. Caesar overpowers Koba and, while lifting Koba from a ledge, refuses to save him and lets him fall to his death.  Malcolm informs Caesar of the impending arrival of human reinforcements. Caesar tells Malcolm the humans will never forgive the apes for the war they started and tells him to leave with his family for safety. As Malcolm slips away into the shadows, Caesar stands before a kneeling mass of apes, ready to lead them into war.

There are some great action scenes as well as emotional and this film has everything you would want to see in this type of film. I recommend it even if you think the film sounds corny but if you liked the 1st film you'll definitely love this one, best of all it's entertaining as hell from start to finish. text: It could just be called Planet of the Apes because I think that most of the apes will get captured by the military and will get taken to a research lab somewhere so they can let scientists find out what to do with the apes. An idea floats into a scientists mind and considers sending them to Mars or a planet that supplies resources such as food and water, this is where the war begins. As they are ready to send them off into space most of the apes are held in cells next to each and communicate saying they should try to escape as they are being escorted to the spaceship. All of the apes begin to fight for there will in the name of freedom as the fight continues in the area around Cape Canaveral. The war beings to slow down as most apes begin to hide for the night unlike the humans where they keep searching for the apes. Morning arrives and Caesar hears gun shots as he sees many apes including his son enter the spaceship. Caesar finds a sniper rifle and rifle and tries to create a diversion with other apes. Caesar shoots one of the soldiers as the search party and the war to find the apes continue. That's all I have if anyone has another other ideas please a reply to my comment. Thank You!
